    region: "Pacific Northwest",
    archetype: "The Block Plan University of the Montana High Country",
    oneSentenceSummary: "The University of Montana Western is the most distinctive public university in Montana — a small institution of 1,200 students in Dillon that runs entirely on Experience One, its own version of the Block Plan where students take one course at a time in 18-day immersive blocks, producing one of the most intimate and experiential educational environments in American public higher education at a tuition that is among the lowest of any four-year institution in the Northwest.",
    pipeline: "Education — UMW's largest program, producing licensed K-12 educators for Montana's rural and reservation school systems. Business — regional placement in Dillon, Butte, and southwestern Montana. Environmental Sciences and Outdoor Recreation — direct field access to Beaverhead National Forest, the Big Hole River watershed, and the Bitterroot Range. Equine Studies — one of the few universities in the Northwest with a dedicated equine science and horsemanship program. Psychology — counseling and human services track for rural Montana placement. Visual Arts and Media. 1,200 undergraduates only.",
    hiddenPathway: "Experience One — UMW's block schedule — is what makes this institution genuinely distinctive among public universities. One course, 18 days, full immersion. The entire class goes on the same field trips, reads the same texts simultaneously, and has the same professor's undivided attention for three weeks. For students who struggle in the fragmented attention of traditional semester scheduling, Experience One is not a gimmick — it is a structural solution. UMW produces teachers, outdoor professionals, and equine specialists who have learned through presence and direct experience rather than distributed multitasking. The Big Hole River — one of the premier fly-fishing rivers in the United States — runs through the Dillon valley and is a field laboratory for environmental science and recreation students.",
    institutionalSecret: "Dillon, Montana sits in the Beaverhead Valley at 5,100 feet — a ranching and mining community of 4,100 people that is among the most genuinely remote college towns in the American West. The Beaverhead-Deerlodge National Forest surrounds the valley. The Pioneer Mountains rise to the west. The Tendoy Mountains to the south. There are no distractions in Dillon that are not of your own making. Students who arrive at UMW intending to disappear into the landscape and emerge four years later with a teaching credential, a fly rod, and a clear sense of who they are tend to do exactly that.",
    theRoom: "A campus of 34 acres in Dillon — a town of 4,100 people in the Beaverhead Valley of southwestern Montana. 1,200 students, approximately 62% living in campus housing. The student body draws primarily from Montana, Idaho, Wyoming, and eastern Washington — students with genuine affinity for rural Western life who have specifically sought out UMW's Experience One model or its equine program. The institution is small enough that the president knows students by name.",
    lifestyle: "Dillon offers what it offers and nothing else: the Big Hole River, the Beaverhead-Deerlodge National Forest, hunting and fishing without competition, stars without light pollution, and the particular silence of the Montana high country. There are no bars with live music, no coffee shops with exposed brick, no farmers markets on Saturdays. Students who need those things will be miserable. Students who do not will be in one of the finest natural environments in America for four years.",
