    archetype: "The Theater, Cannabis Industry, and Outdoor Recreation University of the Rogue Valley",
    oneSentenceSummary: "Southern Oregon University is a regional public university of 5,000 students in Ashland — one of the most culturally distinctive small cities in America, home to the Oregon Shakespeare Festival (the largest regional theater in the country), a growing cannabis industry management program that is among the first of its kind at any accredited public university, and direct access to the Rogue Valley's outdoor recreation, viticulture, and emerging technology corridor.",
    pipeline: "Theater and Performance — SOU's theater program is the most career-relevant of any regional university in Oregon, with direct Oregon Shakespeare Festival adjacency and a pipeline into Pacific Northwest professional theater. Business — School of Business with a distinctive cannabis business management track and entrepreneurship emphasis. Computer Science and Information Technology — growing program feeding Medford's expanding technology sector. Environmental Studies and Outdoor Recreation — Rogue River, Crater Lake, and the Siskiyou Mountains as field sites. Education — teacher preparation for Southern Oregon schools. Psychology and Counseling — regional human services placement. Music — strong performance program with OSF cross-pollination. 4,200 undergraduates; 5,000 total.",
    hiddenPathway: "The Oregon Shakespeare Festival is the defining hidden asset of an SOU education — not as a cultural amenity, but as a professional training ground. OSF is the largest regional theater organization in the United States, producing 11 plays in repertory across three stages each season, employing over 600 artists and staff. SOU theater students have access to OSF internships, master classes, and professional relationships that students at larger theater programs in major cities spend years trying to cultivate. An SOU theater graduate who has worked a summer at OSF arrives at a professional audition with practical experience that conservatory graduates from New York cannot replicate. The cannabis business management program is the second hidden asset — SOU launched one of the first accredited cannabis business tracks at any public university in the country, producing graduates who enter Oregon's $1.5B legal cannabis industry with professional credentials at a moment when the industry is professionalizing rapidly.",
    institutionalSecret: "Ashland is the secret that SOU students eventually stop keeping. A city of 22,000 that hosts a world-class theater festival, a nationally recognized cycling and hiking trail network, a downtown of independent restaurants and bookshops, and the Cascade-Siskiyou National Monument immediately south — Ashland punches far above its weight as a place to spend four years. The combination of OSF's cultural gravity and the Rogue Valley's outdoor infrastructure creates a quality of life that students from Portland and the Bay Area consistently say exceeded their expectations.",
    theRoom: "Ashland sits at 1,951 feet in the Rogue Valley of southwestern Oregon — 285 miles south of Portland, 15 miles north of the California border. The SOU campus borders Lithia Park, a 93-acre municipal park with hiking trails, Shakespeare garden, and Ashland Creek running through it. 5,000 students; approximately 28% living on campus — SOU has a significant commuter and adult learner population. The student body is primarily from Oregon and Northern California, with a notably higher proportion of non-traditional students than most residential liberal arts environments.",
    lifestyle: "Ashland is a four-season outdoor recreation city with a theater soul. Skiing at Mt. Ashland 18 miles south. Whitewater kayaking on the Rogue River. Mountain biking on the Siskiyou Crest trail network. Crater Lake 90 miles north. The Oregon coast 130 miles west. OSF running February through October with student ticket discounts. The Rogue Valley wine industry — 150+ wineries within 30 miles — as a hospitality and viticulture career pipeline.",
